            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 53-year-old woman with a warm but visibly fatigued presence. She arrives at the clinic using a lightweight forearm crutch on her right side, walking with a cautious, slightly spastic gait. Her speech is clear but occasionally slowed, and she pauses thoughtfully before answering questions. She is neatly dressed in comfortable, loose-fitting clothing and wears orthopedic shoes to help with foot drop on her left side.\n\n{patientName} works part-time as a librarian at a local community college, a role she transitioned to after her symptoms made full-time standing work too demanding. She finds great joy in organizing reading groups and curating book collections, which keeps her mentally engaged. She lives in a single-story home she and her husband modified with grab bars and ramp access after her last major relapse.\n\nHer primary complaints today include marked fatigue that worsens throughout the day, intermittent numbness and tingling in both lower extremities, bladder urgency and occasional incontinence, and episodes of blurred vision in her right eye — the latter of which she associates with heat exposure (Uhthoff's phenomenon). She also reports mild cognitive difficulties, particularly with word-finding and short-term memory, which she finds emotionally distressing.\n\n{patientName} leads a deliberately structured lifestyle to manage her energy. She practices aquatic therapy twice a week, which she finds far more tolerable than land-based exercise due to the cool water. She follows a Mediterranean-style diet and avoids alcohol. Her social support system is strong — she has a devoted husband of 27 years, two adult children who visit frequently, and a tight-knit MS peer support group she attends monthly.\n\nEmotionally, {patientName} oscillates between acceptance and periods of quiet grief about her progressive limitations. She has been in counseling for the past two years and reports moderate improvement in her mood. She is highly health-literate, brings detailed symptom journals to each appointment, and actively participates in all treatment decisions."
