            "contentString": "{patientName} was first diagnosed with relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis at age 34, following an episode of unilateral optic neuritis in her right eye and subsequent MRI findings demonstrating multiple periventricular T2 lesions with gadolinium enhancement. She was initially managed with interferon beta-1a, which was later switched to natalizumab after two breakthrough relapses within three years.\n\nOver the past five years, her neurologist has noted evidence of disease progression beyond relapses, and her diagnosis has been updated to secondary progressive MS (SPMS). Her Expanded Disability Status Scale (EDSS) score is currently 4.5. She has had three documented major relapses in the past decade, one of which required a five-day course of IV methylprednisolone and a brief inpatient rehabilitation stay.\n\nComorbidities include: overactive bladder / neurogenic bladder dysfunction (managed with anticholinergic therapy), mild depressive disorder (on antidepressant therapy), osteopenia (linked to prolonged corticosteroid use and reduced mobility), and vitamin D deficiency (on supplementation). She is a non-smoker and does not use recreational substances. She has no history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes. She has a BMI of 23.4.\n\nPast hospitalizations include one inpatient rehabilitation admission (2019) and two short-stay admissions for IV steroid therapy during relapses. She has no known surgical history beyond a laparoscopic cholecystectomy in 2009. She is regularly followed by a neurologist, urologist, and physiotherapist as part of a multidisciplinary MS care team."
